body.plain: This song may be about a lack of communication skills. It is so abstract, however, that may interpretations are possible.

annotations: Je m’inquiète pour tout le monde

The speaker expresses their worry for “every boy and every swordfish/who cannot savour/the joy of a phone call”. This is a moment of self-pity for the speaker, as well as a sorrow for everyone like them who feel incapable of communicating with others.
On sait que les champignons

The speaker states that phones-turned-mushrooms are useless to contact swordfish, especially “the best of all the swordfish”. The speaker feels as though they are incapable, or unworthy, of talking to people in general – this is why they compare themselves to an animal who, obviously, cannot communicate with humans, much less use a telephone.
Vers le champ de tournesols

The speaker compares themselves to a swordfish, who has lost all means of communicating (by losing their phone in a sunflower field). They seem to be potentially isolating themselves, based on the fact that their phone is now “growing mushrooms” – being unused and left to rot.
Il devient un champignon
“he becomes a mushroom”
Salut, j’suis un espadon
“hello, i’m a swordfish”
J’ai perdu mon téléphone
“i have lost my telephone”

We can still be friends

“At the end of the day” could refer to the literal end of the day, which would infer that whoever is speaking to Z needs to hide their friendship. Or it refers to the end of a conflict, and the speaker can stay friends with Z no matter what happened between them.

’Cause in our eyes

Z is not writing as themself, referring to themself as Miss Elaiza.

Dogs are forbidden, but your sticker’s O.K

These lyrics remind me of school lunchroom rules. No pets, no loud music, (no chess?). Z may be talking about starting at a new school.

body.plain: Tippy seems to be a sort of stand-in character for the person the song is being sung to, while Zelda serves the same purpose for the singer.

annotations:
Tippy sleeps and Zelda’s shrinking
 Perhaps, one day, they’ll meet once more
 
 But for now, Zelda’s heart’s still laughing
 And when I see her, I will hold the door

I see Tippy and Zelda as a coping mechanism for the singer dealing with the death of someone close to them (hinted by the voicemails and police sirens prior).

The childlike nature of the nicknames and use of 3rd person seems to be a way for the singer to detach from their reality and the pain they feel, almost as if trying to escape back into a fantasy world where Tippy (who the song is written to) and Zelda (the singer) are still able to be together. This is also seen in the happy imagery and memories associated with the pair:

Happy birthday …. Howling to an electric moon

There still seems to be a bittersweet acceptance of this loss towards the end of the song however, hoping that they’ll meet again and Zelda being prepared to welcome Tippy back by holding the door.

description.plain:
The 7th track of Mansionz debut self-titled album, is similar to “Wicked,” except the roles are switched. Posner & blackbear sing about lovers who are very much in love with them, while Mansionz simply don’t share those feelings, but would rather still have their fun with them.

About halfway through the song, the beat changes, and Posner gives a soliloquy about a girl he pushed out of his life, and her attempting to find her way back in his life.  Although he acts like the love was never mutual, it’s evident by the end of the verse that he was in some way damaged by the relationship.

annotations:
I mean at first, you’re gonna pretend to forget about her
 You know, I’d call her, I don’t know, whatever
 But then, eventually, you really will forget about her
 But what if she comes back first?
 See, that’s the thing is somehow they know not to come back until you really forget

This is a sample from the 1996 movie “Swingers”



Rob: I mean at first you’re going to pretend to forget about her, you’ll not call her, I don’t know, whatever… but then eventually, you really will forget about her.

Mike: Well what if she comes back first?

Rob: Mmmm… see, that’s the thing, is somehow they know not to come back until you really forget.

I’ve gave you wounds and you tell me that they will never heal
 I got your perfume stuck up on my fuckin’ sweatshirt still

The first line is Posner repeating what the ‘lover said’ in that the ‘wounds’ (possibly metaphorical for an argument) won’t ever go away.
This then contrasts with the second line in where he compares his lovers problem to the fact he now has their perfume on his sweatshirt. ‘Still’ suggests he has tried to get rid of the smell but it won’t go away, just like the lover in the previous line.
It also could suggest although they’re now broken up they still have the same problems just in different terms.

Had a flashback, that perfume (yeah)
 Flip you in the bed and you grabbed me soon

That “perfume” Mike has had a flashback about, alludes to the album’s second track, “My Beloved”, which talks about a relationship surviving solely because of the sex.

That is where THIS song continues the story sung about in “My Beloved”. Mike still remembers the girl’s perfume he has previously sung about, for example in the song’s chorus:

Just your perfume, and my beloved

And in Posner’s first verse:

Just the good parts of you and your perfume,
baby

Throughout “A Million Miles”, it will become clear that the relationship has turned sour.
Achey heart, Miley’s dad (ayy)

This line refers to the 1992 hit, “Achy Breaky Heart” by Billy Ray Cyrus, the father of pop sensation, Miley Cyrus. The track’s title reflects Posner’s deep sadness about the end of his relationship.

album.name: 100% Take Home! / Good Morning

annotations:
Please don’t leave the table, I’m still eating
 My plate’s half full

The speaker wants eating with their partner to be a shared experience. In a more metaphorical sense, they crave intimacy and want to be with their partner all the time (‘your absence makes me grow an absence of my own’).
The speaker pleads with their partner to stay with them, creating a rather desperate tone. The line ‘I’m still eating’ suggests that the speaker is not yet finished with their food, nor with their relationship.
Throughout the song, we cannot be certain whether the relationship is actually one-sided, or whether the speaker is simply overly anxious. (However, the latter seems more plausible.)

body.plain: This track is about coping with negative feelings using a ritual.

annotations: The woods are too close to the roads

The narrator complains about the fact that there are roads that are built too close the the woods and the trees. This may be an analogy for herself feeling tightness and stressed – that’s why she feels as though she has to go somewhere quiet to clear her mind, because the roads are closing on her.
It seems as if it’s easier to seek feeling Iimmediate hurt
They are attempting to make themselves feel better through healthy coping mechanisms, however it’s starting to fail and they wish they could self harm instead.
Synthesis, has something gone amiss?

The singer is questioning what when wrong with their thought process. Synthesis is defined as “the final stage in the process of dialectical reasoning, in which a new idea resolves the conflict between thesis and antithesis.”
